          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do you measure contribution margin?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Contribution margin is sales revenue minus variable costs, shown per unit or as a percentage of revenue. A product selling at Rs 1,000 with Rs 620 of materials, freight and payment gateway fees carries a contribution of Rs 380, or 38 per cent. A dashboard tracks that percentage by SKU, channel and customer so loss-making lines surface early."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between contribution margin and gross margin?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Gross margin deducts all cost of goods sold, including fixed factory overhead, while contribution margin deducts only variable costs such as materials, packing, freight and commission. A SKU can show 30 per cent gross margin and 45 per cent contribution margin. Pricing and discount decisions use contribution; the statutory profit and loss statement reports gross margin."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Should GST be excluded from revenue on a contribution margin dashboard?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Revenue on the dashboard should be net of GST, because tax collected is paid to the government and never belongs to the business. GST paid on inputs that is available as input tax credit should equally be stripped out of variable cost. Leaving an 18 per cent GST component on both sides distorts the margin percentage badly."
          }
        }
      ]
